description.text:
Nice Egg Mould to impress your Girlfriend or spouse.

Prerequisites

  • Food proof Silicone http://www.ebay.de/itm/181804247120
  • PLA
  • Eggs

Creating the Mould

  • Print the Mould with PLA and clean it
  • Mix 11 mL of silicone and pour it into the mould
  • Let it cure for 24 hours
  • extract the silicone carefully with a screwdriver and wash it once again

Frying the eggs

  • Put in the silicone mould into a pan with hot oil
  • pour in only a layer of egg and wait until it gets hard
  • then pour in the rest and wait until the rest gets ready

Print the Mould in PLA

title: DJI Mavic Pro Gimbal Lock/Lens Protector-Polar Pro & Taco ND **NinjaFlex**

description.text:
This is a combination gimbal lock/lens protector I designed for the DJI Mavic Pro. It installs from the front and utilizes the tabs that the front feet of the gimbal ride above. It must be printed with a flexible material, I used Ninjflex Semiflex (regular NinjaFlex was too flexible). There have been many cases where the small plastic tab on the back of the camera/gimbal breaks in transit where the factory gimbal lock slides in to hold it in place. This is a simple solution that bypasses the need for the factory lock, and it holds the gimbal in place just as well if not better.

*UPDATE 4.9.17- I have added designs that will fit over the Polar Pro Cinema series as well as the Taco ND series of filters. There is a "PP" and a "T" on the inside of the lens cap for easy identification.

description.text:
Starting with this fantastic thing (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:961881) I made a few modifications
-Found a box in Costco just large enough to hold two rows of spools, 3-4 spools each, total of 6-8. It also fits perfectly in the Lack enclosure I'm building.
-Mounted flat disks (failed print, Attached "Disk" STL should work) outside with the rod holders (1/4" by the way, didn't see it listed on the original page) on the inside. This should relieve stress on the box's plastic sides
-Mounted filament guides inside and outside, drilling the center hole larger to ensure no impediment or scraping. If the inside guides are too close to the spools, I'll remove them.
-Created the attached "Filament Parking" STL in Tinkercad using the filament guide; the holes are blocked, so it's a decent spot to stick the end of the filament when not in use
-I printed several sets of this spool holder (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:767317)

Note: Photo shows 0.5 Kg AIO Robotics spools.

Enjoy!

Updates:
-2017-03-31: Added picture of box label, includes dimensions. Hardware I used: 3mm x 8mm screws/nuts (x18), 3mm x 12mm screws/nuts (x24). Recommend 3mm x 10mm screws/nuts (x42) if you have them on hand. Recommended remix: convert the filament parking piece into a 6-slot (or n-slot) filament pass-through. Still waiting for rods.

title: K8200 Frame clip and locking pin for Velleman 3D printer

description.text:
You probably discovered that mounting any accessories on the printer's frame is a bit inconvenient. It is a good idea with these square nuts slid in the frame but unfortunately if you want to add something after the printer is fully assembled - it can be very ungrateful.
Some of the areas are easy to be modified, like the vertical aluminium profiles - it requires just removing the top caps. However, some areas are very hard to access (like the Z carriage arm) - you would need to tear the printer apart to get into the groove in the aluminium profile. My first thought was to design a locking pin that would slide through the slot and then lock if rotated 90°. I have created rectangular holes on the sides of the clip to allow the pin slide through. Flat M3 bolt + washer or flat M4 bolt can be used. More details on my blog: http://ljwinkler.blogspot.ie/2014/01/frame-clip-and-locking-pin-for-velleman.html

This is a replacement part for a  The actual part is a replacement for Bruck lighting system part #190 515 sw Endeinspeisung. Happy Endings!

I'd be shocked if anyone ever printed this as it has a unique function, however this story embodies the amazing potential of the 3D Printing revolution. It begins with a discontinued part that would require ultimate replacement of a Track Lighting system widely used in our facility. While I could have done the geometry in AutoCad or similar, I decided to see if such a project was in the realm of more accesible programs like Tinkercad the answer plays out in the commentary section of Tinkercad. https://tinkercad.com/things/3Pkh5wWSF8a

Printed in 3 parts. Cap can be securely pressed onto shaft, but I also used some superglue. I advise printing as a solid object. It a lock feature to prevent the tube from unrolling. Simply press the shaft inward to engage the lock and pull out to disengage.

I didn't like that the original was somewhat hard to print with the overhangs, and the shape of the spinner was not comfortable to use. This is easier to print and slightly larger.

I recently made a v2 after several months of use, because one of the two inner bars broke with some force. This one is slightly thicker and better to print, in the hopes that the additional thickness takes more force to shear.

PAWZ are wonderful balloon-like dog booties, but can be awkward to put on your dog's feet. However, if the bootie's mouth is stretched over the narrow end of the tool, the tool and bootie can be slipped over the dog's paw, and then the bootie slipped off the tool and around the dog's leg, allowing the tool to be withdrawn.

The tools is designed for use with the red "small" size PAWZ, but it should be able to be scaled as needed provided the wall thickness is maintained.

The photos show the application steps (using my fingers to represent a paw; I'd need an extra arm to demonstrate on my dog and take the photo at the same time).

description.text:
I am just adding an edited version of FPV_Quadcopter__Tinycopter95_SciSky_FlightController_85mm_Motors because I edited the upper frame portion for different versions of video transmitters.

This frame was inspired by the Micro 105 FPV Quadcopter by punkkills - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1221911. I am using the same components (flightcontroller, videoTX, camera, similar motors). My intension was, to have the camera tiltable before flight, so I can adjust it upwards for fast forward flight and straight or even downwards, if I am flying indors.

The size is 95mm and the overall weight is ~54g with battery (~32g without). The frame itself (including the caps to protect the motor wires) is less than 6g (ABS).

I have tried to save weight and make mounting / dismounting easier by using snap-joints
The Flight Controller and the TX snap to their Frames, Camera slides into the mounting and will be snapped in the frame, frame parts snap together...
As every 3D printer has different tolerances, this might need some tweaking.

Parts List

I had purchased everything at GetFPV.com and here is a parts list.
-OverSky Scisky Micro F3 Brushed Flight Control built-in RX option
-OverSky Scisky video transmitter VTX 40CH 25MW on Scisky board
-Lumenier RX0820-12 Black Chrome Micro Brushed Motor Set (2 CW, 2 CCW)
-Lumenier SM-600 Super Mini - 600TVL Wide Angle Camera

description.text:
My first attempt a 3D modelling...

I modified BoyDrone's parts cooler to fit my needs/wants. I just upgraded to a E3D v6 hotend on my Flsun I3 printer and the fan mounts in the front didn't match. So I modified his to remove part of the front and added a mounting hole for the fan. I used an M2x4mm screw I had from some Quadcopter builds but any small screw will do.

You'll probably need to make a hole on the fan housing where this will mount. Just line the tab on the outside to find where the hole needs to go and use an xacto knife to bore a small hole for the screw.

I made 2 versions. A raised version that fits the v6 hotend height and a flat version that will fit the v5 hotends a little better. The flat will also work with the v6 but the clearance is very tight.

The purpose of this project is to determine whether or not using 3D printed graphs are helpful for Calculus III students to visualize 3D planes and surfaces, thus increasing their understanding of those functions. These graphs can be used however the teacher sees fit throughout the course of his or her class. These models would be most effective as a visualization tool to supplement a lesson on 3D functions and what they look like.

Here is a very simple design for a robotic arm that uses three 28BYJ-48 motors. It can be hooked up to essentially any microcontroller, although I would highly recommend using some sort of an Arduino as I have already written a sketch for this method. I have also written a sketch in Processing to send controls over USB from the NumPad. Setting it up is as easy as connecting the motor to the board in a proper order, and running the sketches.

Getting Started

  1. Install Processing and the Arduino IDE
  2. Download the sketches
  3. Unzip the sketches
  4. Upload "RoboticArmStepperControlSketch" to your Arduino if you have one
  5. Run "RoboticArmProccessingSketch" in Processing (Click the window that pops up)
  6. Use the numpad's side keys to control the arm

Physical Layout on the Board
In my setup I used PWM pins 13-2 on an Elegoo Mega2560 R3 (A spinoff of the Arduino Mega). You can use any pin layout you want. Just define the pins on lines 18-20 of the code. In the code I have the motors set at 85-70 RPMs. If you'd like a little more strength you can go slower than this by changing lines 53-55, but it's not necessary. The values I used work well with the corresponding weights the motors bare.

Controls
The left side of the numpad (Keys 7, 4, 1) is for independent motor controls, along with the right side for the opposite movement. Keys 8 and 2 move both the arms together. I haven't quite figured out how to send multiple keys through processing, and until then, keys 8 and 2 will be used for the simultaneous control of the motors.
